@node "Main" "Welcome to WES"

@{jcenter}@{fg shine}The Warp Emulation Suite v1.0@{fg text}

@{jleft}  Welcome to WES for Amiga WarpUP systems!

  WES (Warp Emulation Suite) consists of a master controlling program, WarpKickstart, and a suite of emulation engines, which allow you to emulate a large number of machines.  As time goes by, more and more engines will be added to the suite.

  @{"Requirements" link "Requirements"}
  @{"WarpKickstart, WES' master controller" link "WarpKickstart"}
  @{"Engines Supported" link "Engines Supported"}
  @{"Directory Structure" link "Directory Structure"}
  @{"Usage" link "Usage"} including @{"Command Line Parameters" link "Command Line Parameters"}
  @{"Screen Modes Suported" link "Screen Modes Supported"}
  @{"History" link "History"}
  @{"The Unwritten Future" link "The Unwritten Future"}

  The latest version of WES can always be found at http://www.powerup.com.au/~cward and on Aminet.

@{jcenter}@{fg shine}Code HQ - Never surrender - Amiga always!

@endnode

@node "Amiga" "The Amiga - One Amazing Computer!"

@{jcenter}@{fg shine}Amiga@{fg text}

@{jleft}  The greatest computer on the planet.  Created by Jay Miner, to whom we owe so much.  Best experienced with a Power PC upgrade, hard drive full of demos and large stereo.

@endnode

@node "Command Line Parameters"

@{jcenter}@{fg shine}Command Line Parameters@{fg text}

@{jleft}  Performance Related Parameters

  @{"-blithack" link "blithack"}
  @{"-blitppc" link "blitppc"}
  @{"-depth" link "depth"}
  @{"-interlace" link "interlace"}
  @{"-sr" link "sr"}

  Miscellaneous Parameters

  @{"-hidesmall" link "hidesmall"}
  @{"-joystick" link "joystick"}
  @{"-snap" link "snap"}
  @{"-soundcard" link "soundcard"}

@endnode

@node "blithack" "-blithack"

@{jcenter}@{fg shine}-blithack@{fg text}

@{jleft}  When a WES engine is executing a ROM, it renders the Screen output into a buffer (we will call this the Frame Buffer) which is later on copied to the physical Screen.  Because Screen hardware on many Amigas is so slow, this can take almost as long as actually executing the ROM!

  As an attempt to take this processing load off the PPC, Screen updates are done by the Master Controller, so that the PPC can go on to create the next frame in parallel.  However, because the 68k and PPC are accessing the Frame Buffer simultaneously, each needs it's own Frame Buffer.  This is unfortunately a little slower than only having the one Frame Buffer.

  The -blithack parameter will cause both the 68k and the PPC to use the same Frame Buffer for rendering, which can give an impressive speed increase.  Although perfectly safe, it is a matter of luck whether this works.  For some ROMs the screen will be corrupted and for others it will be perfect!

  If it does work then it can often mean the difference between a game being too slow to play, and being just fast enough.  So for the slower games, give it a try.

  Note: This parameter will be ignored if the PPC is being used for output.  Please see the @{"-blitppc" link "blitppc"} parameter for more details.

@endnode

@node "blitppc" "-blitppc"

@{jcenter}@{fg shine}-blitppc@{fg text}

@{jleft}  As explained in the section on the @{"-blithack" link "blithack"} parameter, by default the Master Controller copies the rendered Frame Buffer to the physical Screen.

  In the case of an Amiga with a very slow grafix subsystem such as a Zorro based grafix card or AGA, this can improve the speed of WES.  However, on an Amiga with a fast grafix subsystem such as a CyberVision/PPC, BVision/PPC or a PCI based card running on the upcoming Mediator daughterboard, it is faster to use the PPC to copy the Frame Buffer to the physical Screen.

  The -blitppc parameter will cause the PPC to perform the Frame Buffer copy.  However, it will be ignored if AGA is used for output.  See the @{"Screen Modes Suported" link "Screen Modes Supported"} to see what Screen Modes are supported by WES.

@endnode

@node "depth" "-depth"

@{jcenter}@{fg shine}-depth@{fg text}

@{jleft}  This parameter, although in the PC documentation, is important enough to mention here.

  As of Version 0.37 Beta 16, most games are emulated in 8 bit mode, but some, most notably many NeoGeo games, are emulated in 16 bit mode.  For any Amiga other than the Amiga One, this is too much to handle because of the sheer amount of data that must be transferred to the screen for each Frame.

  Using this parameter as "-depth 8" you can force WES to emulate 16 bit games in 8 bit mode.  Because the engine has less colours to use, some games may not look as good, but at least they will be playable!

@endnode

@node "Directory Structure"

@{jcenter}@{fg shine}Directory Structure@{fg text}

@{jleft}  Because WES supports many engines, it requires a specific directory structure so that each engine can find its ROMs etc.

  Generally speaking, there will be a directory such as "ROMs" and under this will be directories for each engine.  The ROMs for each engine will be placed in here.

  Currently the engine layout is as follows:

   Dat
   Docs
   Docs/MAME
   Docs/MESS
   Docs/NeoPocott
   Engines
   ROMs
   ROMs/MAME
   ROMs/MESS
   ROMs/NeoPocott
   Samples
   Samples/MAME
   Snap

  Executing the script called "MakeDirs" in the main WES archive will create this directory structure for you.

@endnode

@node "Engines Supported"

@{jcenter}@{fg shine}Engines Supported@{fg text}

@{jleft}  Currently WES supports six engines, with more to follow.  The main engine, that everyone wants, of course, is MAME.  I think that most people would consider the others a bonus.  :-)

  MAME is a BIG engine which is only getting bigger, requiring more and more CPU power and memory.  Latest news is that future versions of MAME will only support 16 bit screen modes, which are a little too much for our Amigas to handle, even those with CyberVision/PPC and BVision/PPC cards.

  The solution was to create a new engine called "WarpMAME Classic."  This engine is based on an older, faster version of MAME that can output to 8 bit screens.  Much thought went into which version of MAME would be the best to use for this, and finally it was decided that v0.37 Beta 5 would be the best.  v0.37 Beta 16, the last version of MAME before the switch to 16 bit screens, is considerably slower than Beta 5, so it was decided that this would not have made a good choice.

  So from now on, when new versions of MAME are released on the PC, they will be ported to WES and will be activated with the -mame parameter.  Using the -mameclassic parameter will cause WarpMAME Classic to be used instead, which is good for older games that you want to run at full speed.  Of course, updates to WarpMAME Classic will also be released from time to time, so that it can also benefit from updats to WES, such as Window-on-Workbench and AHI support.

  The current list of engines supported by WES is as follows:

  WarpMAME
  WarpMAME Classic
  WarpNeoMAME
  WarpNeoMAME Classic
  WarpMESS
  WarpNeoPocott

@endnode

@node "hidesmall" "-hidesmall"

@{jcenter}@{fg shine}-hidesmall@{fg text}

@{jleft}  This parameter will restrict the list of Screen Modes displayed in the RTGMaster requester, such that those which are too small for the ROM being executed to fit on, are hidden.

@endnode

@node "History"

@{jcenter}@{fg shine}History

@{jleft}  Version 1.0@{fg text}

  - Changed from being MAME and MESS specific to a general purpose emulation system

  - Added Neo Geo Pocket Colour engine

  - Added support for all 7 buttons on the CD32 Joypad

  - Will now run without lowlevel.library present (but in this case will only use 1 joystick button)

  - .dat files now go into their own directory called "Dat" under the WES directory

  - A requester now pops up when ROMs are missing or invalid

  - Added dozens of small improvements not worth mentioning here, or forgotten about!

  @{fg shine}Version 0.37 Beta 5@{fg text}

  - Changed the version numbering system to be in line with the PC numbering system, as can be seen by the heading of this entry.  :-)

  - Added support for AGA and 16 bit games

  - Implemented a 68k Parallel Processing system to reduce context switching overhead

  - Changed the "Insert Coin" key from 3 to 5, to be consistent with other ports

  - Fixed up the fps status display and enabled auto frameskip

  - Upgraded to GCC 2.95.2.  All CPU cores compile with full optimisation now

  - Fixed a small bug which meant that if you used the -hidesmall option, sometimes screenmodes which were too small for a particular game would still be displayed

  - Implemented native Paula Sound support.  A big thank you here to Amidog for his Paula source code

  - Added support for gamepads using lowlevel.library, with hardware hitting fallback code for joysticks which don't work (such as my StarCursor).  Use Joystick port for Player 1 and a Joystick/gamepad plugged into the Mouse port for Player 2

  - Fixed a bug which was causing games which faded in/out to do so really slowly.  It was a bit embarassing so I'm not telling you what it was.  ;-P

  - Added support for the Nostalgia Emulator front end, for WarpNeoMAME.  The old version could be used with Nostalgia, but this one integrates better

  - Added a graphical loading display, for when large ROMs take along time to load

  - Added dozens of small improvements not worth mentioning here, or forgotten about!

  @{fg shine}Alpha v0.4@{fg text}

  - Updated source to Version 0.36 Beta 11

  - Internal Sound emulation is now enabled by default, as some games rely on it.  However, speciyfing "-soundcard 0" will disable it

  - Second joystick will now work for two player games

  @{fg shine}Alpha v0.3@{fg text}

  - Compiled a NeoGeo only version

  - Updated source to Version 0.36 Beta 10

  - Joystick support is temporarily broken after updating to new source as the interface had completely changed.  Will be fixed in the next release!

  - Added a version string

  - Seeing as there is no sound support yet, I disabled sound emulation, gaining an extra 5 FPS for 1943 :-)

  - Tested and verified that Zipped ROMs work (there is a version of Zip in Geek Gadgets if you want to Zip your ROMs)

  - Now centres game screens properly when blitting them to the physical Screen

  - Screenshot directory is now created if it doesn't exist, and can be specified with the -snap command line option.  Defaults to Snap

  - -hidesmall command line option will cause the RTGMaster Screen mode Requester to only display Screen modes which the selected game will completely fit on

  - Vector and dirty rectangle games now work, although this needs some more work done

  - Enabled copyright & game info screens

  @{fg shine}Alpha v0.2@{fg text}

  - *Most* keys are now implemented.  These include Tab, Tilde (~), F3, F4, Del (FPS on/off), Help (Save snapshot), Enter.  There are still a couple that have to be done, but it is strange because the documentation and the source don't always match, so I will have to check the PC DOS version to see what the "standard" keys are.  It seemed logical to map the PC F11 and F12 keys to Del and Help

  - Snapshot now works but you have to have a Snap dir under the WES directory

  - Naughty hardware hitting joystick support added!  I will put in proper lowlevel.library support soon, with a concurrent m68k task

  - Text printing fuckups which were happening with my old hacky blitting routine are gone now that I'm using the quality rtgmaster.library one.  :-)

  - You can select the "Use WB Window" gadget and it will open a WB window, but nothing appears yet.  I'm working on it.  :-)  Any ideas Steffen?  I'll send you the video code.

  - Fixed a dumb bug which caused WarpMAME to crash if you selected cancel in the RTGMaster screen selection requester (forgetting to return the right value!)

  @{fg shine}Alpha 0.1@{fg text}

  - Initial private Alpha release

@endnode

@node "interlace" "-interlace"

@{jcenter}@{fg shine}-interlace@{fg text}

@{jleft}  Specifying this parameter will cause WES to only render every second scanline of each Frame.  It will alternate between rendering all odd numbered scanlines and all even numbered scanlines.  This causes some visual artifacts but results in an impressive speed increase on slow grafix systems such as Zorro based grafix cards and AGA.

@endnode

@node "joystick"

@{jcenter}@{fg shine}-joystick@{fg text}

@{jleft}  By default, lowlevel.library is used for reading joystick input.  However, some joysticks (in particular, my favourite StarCursor joystick) don't work with lowlevel.library, and this parameter can be used to force direct hardware reading of the joystick ports for these joysticks.

  Specify the -joystick parameter followed by a number which indicates the method to use for reading the two joystick ports.  The number is checked by WES in a bitwise fashion;  bit 0 represents joystick port 1 and bit 1 represents joystick port 2.  A set bit means to hit the hardware for that port and a clear bit means to use lowlevel.library.

  For non programmers who don't understand the bits and bytes, simply use the following handy list of values for the parameter.  :-)

  0 - Use lowlevel.library for both joysticks (default)

  1 - Use hardware for joystick 1 and lowlevel.library for joystick 2

  2 - Use lowlevel.library for joystick 1 and hardware for joystick 2

  3 - Use hardware for both joysticks

  Note that if you force the joystick to be read via hardware then you will also fall back to single button joystick support.  :-(  If this is a problem for you, contact @{"me" link "About The Author"} and I'll see what I can do.

  When using a CD32 Joypad with lowlevel.library, the start button on Joypad 1 emulates the "Player 1 Start" button and the start button on Joypad 2 emulates the "Player 2 Start" button.

@endnode

@node "Requirements"

@{jcenter}@{fg shine}Requirements

@{jleft}  An @{"Amiga" link "Amiga"}

  @{fg text}You won't get far without one of these.  :-)

  @{fg shine}lowlevel.library@{fg text}

  For multi-button joystick input.

  @{fg shine}reqtools.library@{fg text}

  For selecting the Screen on which to output.

  @{fg shine}A PowerPC@{fg text}

  Most of WES' engines were written by PC programmers, and therefore require obscene amounts of CPU power!

  @{fg shine}Lots of memory.@{fg text}

  See "A PowerPC" :-)

  @{fg shine}A big Hard Drive@{fg text}

  For all those lovely ROMs.

  @{fg shine}A CyberVision/PPC or BVision/PPC@{fg text}

  Well, this is not absolutely necessary as WES should run happily on any grafix card and also on AGA.  But one thing that I have realised when working on WES is that a slow grafix subsystem such a Zorro based grafix card or AGA, is the biggest cause of slowdown for most games, so WES will run a lot smoother on a fast card.  My friend's A1200/603e/BVision-PPC can outrun my A4000/604e/CV64-3D on most games - how embarassing!

@endnode

@node "snap" "-snap"

@{jcenter}@{fg shine}-snap@{fg text}

@{jleft}  By default, when you hit the Help key, WES will dump a Snapshot into the "Snap" directory, which resides under the directory from which WES was run.  You can alter this directory with this parameter.

@endnode

@node "soundcard" "-soundcard"

@{jcenter}@{fg shine}-soundcard@{fg text}

@{jleft}  This parameter, although in the PC documentation, has been slightly modified for the Amiga.  Specify the -soundcard parameter, followed by a number representing the Amiga sound output device that you wish to use.  This can be one of the following:-

  0 - Disable sound totally
  1 - /dev/null
  2 - Paula

  For playing games that your Amiga can't quite keep up with it is best to specify device 0, which will cause WES to not call the internal sound emulation routines.  This can speed things up quite a bit.  However, some games do not work properly when their sound hardware is not emulated, so for these specify specify device 1.  This takes more CPU time than device 0, but less than 2 or 3.

  If your Amiga is powerful enough for the game being emulated, specify device 2.

  If you do not specify this parameter you will be propmpted for a sound device at startup.

@endnode

@node "sr" "-sr"

@{jcenter}@{fg shine}-sr@{fg text}

@{jleft}  This parameter, although in the PC documentation, is important enough to mention here.

  Because the current PPC based Amiga is only just powerful enough to run MAME, it can suffer considerable slowdown when sound is being emulated.  This parameter allows you to specify a sample rate in Hz, between 5000 and 22050 Hz.  By default, sound is played back at 22050 Hz.

@endnode

@node "The Unwritten Future"

@{jcenter}@{fg shine}The Unwritten Future@{fg text}

@{jleft}  Yes, yes, I know that I'm a fucking lamer.  I know that in the past there have been long periods of inactivity between releases of WarpMAME!  I actually didn't have an Amiga for many months as my old one died, and when I finally got one it took a LONG time to get a decent compiler for it.  Our poor old Amiga is a LONG way behind the times when it comes to compiler technology.  I have had to build a custom version of GCC on my Macintosh Linux/PPC system, and that took a long time to figure out.  Having no Amiga, followed by no decent compiler, can totally destroy one's motivation for programming!  So there is my excuse.  :-P

  But this period is over and things are under way again, as can be seen by this release of WES.  I won't list any future improvements here, but suffice to say that they will come, along with regular releases!

  If you have any ideas, criticisms or bug reports, feel free to write to me at cward@powerup.com.au!

@endnode

@node "Usage"

@{jcenter}@{fg shine}Usage@{fg text}

@{jleft}  To start WES, you will launch WarpKickstart, the 68k Master Controller, described in gory detail @{"here" link "WarpKickstart"}.  The command line template is as follows:-

  WarpKickstart [ROM Name] [Emulation Engine] <Parameter 1> ... <Parameter X>

  The ROM Name and Emulation Engine parameters must be specified.  Following these are any number of optional parameters, as described in the @{"Command Line Parameters" link "Command Line Parameters"} section.  The Emulation Engine parameter will be one of the following:-

  -mame
  -mameclassic
  -neomame
  -neomameclassic
  -mess
  -neopocott

  Note that the appropriate Engine must be in the "Engines" directory.  An example WES session is as follows:-

  WarpKickstart 1943 -mame -frameskip 0 -soundcard 2

@{jleft}

@endnode

@node "Screen Modes Supported"

@{jcenter}@{fg shine}Screen Modes Supported@{fg text}

@{jleft}  Because WES is such a huge system emulating such a large number of machines, it's internal Screen Output routines are quite complex and can't output all ROMs to all Screen Modes.  This is not because of bad programming, but is due to the complexity of the program and the amount of time needed to write all of the required Screen Output routines.

  Below is a "truth table" of what WES display types can currently be output to what Amiga Screen Modes.  Many "N's" will turn to "Y's" as time goes on.  :-)

  +------------+----------------------------------------------+
  |            | 68k CGX/P96 | PPC CGX/P96 | 68k AGA | PPC AGA|
  +------------+-------------+-------------+---------+--------+
  |16 bit      |      Y      |      Y      |    N    |    N   |
  +------------+-------------+-------------+---------+--------+
  |8 bit       |      Y      |      Y      |    Y    |    N   |
  +------------+-------------+-------------+---------+--------+
  |16 bit dirty|      N      |      N      |    N    |    N   |
  +------------+-------------+-------------+---------+--------+
  |8 bit dirty |      N      |      Y      |    N    |    N   |
  +------------+-------------+-------------+---------+--------+

  By default, WES will always use the Master Controller for Screen Output.  It will only use the PPC if it is unable to use the 68k according to the table above, or if the user requests use of the PPC with the @{"-blitppc" link "blitppc"} parameter.  Please not that it is usually @{fg shine}faster@{fg text} to use the 68k Master Controller for screen output, as the output can be done in parallel with the emulation.

  For the most part, you can run WES without concern for this table.  It is only there for people who like to play with the @{"-blitppc" link "blitppc"} and @{"-blithack" link "blithack"} parameters, to try to get extra speed out of ROMs.

  Please note that when running WES, it will only display the Screen Modes which can be used for the ROM being executed.  If no Screen Modes are available for that ROM, the message "No appropriate screen modes available!" will be displayed.  If you encounter this, please contact cward@powerup.com.au with the name of the ROM that you were trying to run and your hardware setup, and I will endeavour to add support for that configuration in the next release of WES.

  Please also note that when outputting to an AGA Screen, WES will align the ROM's display area on a four byte boundary, for efficiency.  This means that some ROMs may be slightly off centre horizontally.

@endnode

@node "WarpKickstart"

@{jcenter}@{fg shine}WarpKickstart@{fg text}

@{jleft}  WES comes with a 68k program, that is both its Master Controller and a means of offloading processing from the PowerPC.  This includes AGA c2p, RTG blitting and sound output, as well as reducing the number of context switches required to an absolute minimum.  This works by using a queue of commands, so that if, for instance, the PPC needs to do something such as setting the palette, then instead of doing it straight away, which would require a context switch, it can queue up a command to the 68k, thereby having the palette update done for "free" at the next update.  One update is done per frame.

  The Master Controller resides in it's own file, "WarpKickstart," as it is required all emulation engines.  To run an emulator you will actually run this executable, which will then invoke the PPC executable, establishing the required 68k<->PPC communication link.

@endnode

